1
00:00:01,127 --> 00:00:01,589
Okay.

2
00:00:04,051 --> 00:00:11,223
So now these are the five remembrances that the Buddha says will really awaken our desire to practice.

3
00:00:11,944 --> 00:00:15,830
So the first one's there.

4
00:00:16,951 --> 00:00:17,472
Just a minute.

5
00:00:17,532 --> 00:00:18,073
Why is that?

6
00:00:18,993 --> 00:00:19,315
Oh, yeah.

7
00:00:19,335 --> 00:00:19,716
Excuse me.

8
00:00:19,955 --> 00:00:21,397
I'm at the end.

9
00:00:21,378 --> 00:00:22,359
Here we are.

10
00:00:23,240 --> 00:00:27,687
So the idea is that we're not thinking about it so much.

11
00:00:28,669 --> 00:00:31,013
It's more sort of getting into the feel of these things.

12
00:00:31,472 --> 00:00:37,682
So remember, in our death-phobic culture, we don't like to think about these things.

13
00:00:38,384 --> 00:00:47,317
For instance, every morning, I'm sure we all wake up presuming, without any shadow of a doubt, that we will actually live throughout the day.

14
00:00:48,139 --> 00:00:49,140
And there's no...

15
00:00:49,912 --> 00:00:58,241
There's no logical reason for believing that because, as you know, accidents happen, things happen, we can die just on a whim.

16
00:00:59,984 --> 00:01:02,206
But we don't remind ourselves.

17
00:01:03,427 --> 00:01:16,561
So what this is trying to do is say, look, every morning when you wake up, the first contemplation is to rejoice that you've actually woken up and then to remind yourself that this could be the last day.

18
00:01:17,015 --> 00:01:21,944
One way or the other, or at least you could fall seriously ill and so on.

19
00:01:22,605 --> 00:01:24,167
Definitely you'll be getting older.

20
00:01:24,347 --> 00:01:25,750
There's no way you can get around that.

21
00:01:26,951 --> 00:01:35,546
So the sickness there, you see, that's a preparation for terminal sickness if we have one.

22
00:01:36,049 --> 00:01:43,882
And it's also just basically recognizing that the body can fall ill. Now, we'll come to how to do this in a minute.

23
00:01:44,262 --> 00:01:50,512
So there's your aging business and lots of things that the Buddha says about death.

24
00:01:51,393 --> 00:01:52,534
We just read one of them.

25
00:01:52,555 --> 00:01:53,917
Death is inescapable.

26
00:01:54,498 --> 00:01:55,659
Everybody must die.

27
00:01:55,719 --> 00:02:00,387
Remember, the reminder of your lifespan is decreasing continuously.

28
00:02:00,822 --> 00:02:03,284
That's a nice little reflection.

29
00:02:04,025 --> 00:02:10,473
And death will come regardless of whether or not we have made time to practice the Dharma.

30
00:02:11,915 --> 00:02:13,717
So wealth cannot help.

31
00:02:14,278 --> 00:02:18,443
So all this is little ways in which he encourages us.

32
00:02:19,205 --> 00:02:30,019
And then number four is recognizing that in the end we part and are separated from everyone and everything dear and agreeable to us.

33
00:02:30,286 --> 00:02:34,431
And then finally, there's the contemplations of karma.

34
00:02:36,474 --> 00:02:36,776
Right?

35
00:02:37,096 --> 00:02:43,324
So now, what I'm going to do is just put the bare stuff up there like that.

36
00:02:44,066 --> 00:02:45,829
Now, there's two ways of doing it.

37
00:02:46,008 --> 00:02:54,341
One way is just to repeat the sentence into your heart, getting the feel of what your reaction is.

38
00:02:55,562 --> 00:02:58,807
And you might say, this body is subject to disease.

39
00:03:00,020 --> 00:03:04,646
This body, this body is subject to disease.

40
00:03:05,067 --> 00:03:07,691
This body is subject to disease.

41
00:03:08,391 --> 00:03:08,853
You know what I mean?

42
00:03:08,872 --> 00:03:15,421
You sort of play with the words to try and get some sort of recognition of its truth value.

43
00:03:16,043 --> 00:03:20,669
And what you're interested in is, of course, how you're reacting to it.

44
00:03:21,510 --> 00:03:21,951
Okay?

45
00:03:22,573 --> 00:03:24,254
Either with a sense of

46
00:03:24,403 --> 00:03:27,889
anxiety, there's anxiety there, there's fear, etc.

47
00:03:28,348 --> 00:03:36,419
Now you can up the ante by actually bringing to mind those things that you're particularly afraid of.

48
00:03:37,080 --> 00:03:50,139
So this body, you know, is subject to disease, and it could be Alzheimer's, or it could be a paralysing neurological disease, or it could be cancer.

49
00:03:50,579 --> 00:03:53,483
We've always got something that really worries us.

50
00:03:53,733 --> 00:03:58,296
And if you bring that to mind, again, you're looking at your fear.

51
00:03:58,777 --> 00:04:05,563
See, remember, this is the self, not wanting to die, not wanting to fall ill, not wanting to age.

52
00:04:06,564 --> 00:04:21,798
And in getting in contact with that, as soon as those feelings come, to be open to them, you know, to receive them, you know, to accept that this is the way our relationship is to this.

53
00:04:22,083 --> 00:04:25,348
And then just to allow it to evaporate a little bit.

54
00:04:25,968 --> 00:04:30,055
Now, there might not be time to do that in the first run.

55
00:04:30,757 --> 00:04:33,360
But after we've done the first run, I'll lead you to it.

56
00:04:34,141 --> 00:04:38,910
And you can either continue or just go back to Vipassana.

57
00:04:39,514 --> 00:04:55,262
And also the other thing is that when the fear, the grief, the aversion, the aversion comes, it's easier to accept it if you receive it with a sense of care.

58
00:04:55,242 --> 00:05:00,612
So there's a part of the heart that is not particularly happy and it's not feeling well.

59
00:05:01,293 --> 00:05:10,129
And you would sort of hug it, shall we say, as you would a child who's suffering one of these mental states.

60
00:05:11,223 --> 00:05:14,286
So there's two ways there, just repeating the phrase.

61
00:05:14,786 --> 00:05:23,716
This is what it says in the Visuddhimagga, the path of purification by Buddhaghosa, just to repeat it.

62
00:05:24,016 --> 00:05:32,264
But I think you can also use your imagination to get in touch with how we feel about these things.

63
00:05:33,627 --> 00:05:37,170
And so we just repeat these things to ourselves, aging and then death.

64
00:05:38,050 --> 00:05:39,593
And then there's that one about

65
00:05:40,079 --> 00:05:43,202
parting, separated from everyone.

66
00:05:43,504 --> 00:05:47,389
And here again, you can just say it, say it in different ways.

67
00:05:48,850 --> 00:05:56,680
And of course, you can bring to mind what it is you are most attached to and what it will be a pain to leave.

68
00:05:58,023 --> 00:06:04,651
And of course, you can also extend that to be parted from everyone because they're leaving you

69
00:06:05,137 --> 00:06:06,821
People die, people leave.

70
00:06:08,502 --> 00:06:11,047
And again, you can use your imagination.

71
00:06:11,127 --> 00:06:13,651
So what does that mean to you?

72
00:06:15,153 --> 00:06:18,557
And then finally, karma, which has a certain brightness to it.

73
00:06:18,658 --> 00:06:19,699
We are the owners.

74
00:06:21,021 --> 00:06:22,764
We do possess our own actions.

75
00:06:23,865 --> 00:06:27,071
We are responsible for them, body, speech and mind.

76
00:06:27,391 --> 00:06:32,800
But here, of course, we've got the ones that are unwholesome, but the ones that are also wholesome.

77
00:06:33,067 --> 00:06:47,168
And we get either the up and commons of something we've done which is unskillful, and we get the reward of doing something which is skillful.

78
00:06:47,187 --> 00:06:48,610
So we inherit the results.

79
00:06:52,375 --> 00:06:56,341
We're born out of our karma.

80
00:06:57,242 --> 00:06:58,584
It's always with us.

81
00:06:58,851 --> 00:07:03,418
Our relationships are formed through our karma.

82
00:07:05,500 --> 00:07:09,206
And in fact, you could say that, relatively speaking, that's what we are.

83
00:07:09,286 --> 00:07:13,552
We are our relationships.

84
00:07:13,572 --> 00:07:14,692
And you depend on them.

85
00:07:14,713 --> 00:07:16,134
You depend on your karma.

86
00:07:17,637 --> 00:07:20,600
So then, we'll run through that.

87
00:07:21,221 --> 00:07:25,247
And what I'll do is I'll time a minute for each sentence.

88
00:07:26,425 --> 00:07:33,071
And then I'll remind you to do the reflections on gratitude.

89
00:07:33,591 --> 00:07:39,877
So you always have to balance these negative reflections with something positive.

90
00:07:41,017 --> 00:07:44,440
So here I've just put a few things up.

91
00:07:44,461 --> 00:07:46,423
Excuse me.

92
00:07:46,463 --> 00:07:54,689
You know, gratitude for being born, your mother, for your family, your father, friends, your upbringing and education.

93
00:07:54,750 --> 00:07:55,790
We bring that to mind.

94
00:07:56,209 --> 00:08:03,476
all the medical practitioners who've helped you, all the gifts of our society, of our culture, the world, of nature.

95
00:08:04,017 --> 00:08:24,057
And then finally, just to remind ourselves that this life is precious, that here the Buddha says we have this combination of joy and woe, and the intuitive intelligence sharp enough to find our way out of samsara, the world of constantly going round and round.

96
00:08:24,745 --> 00:08:52,389
and finally just the preciousness of the dharma so we can spend some time doing that and then I shall leave it to you as to how you want to proceed and then we'll do the refuges and precepts okay so when I've finished it I'll try and put all that in one page if you want to glance at it but at the moment I'll keep it like this

97
00:09:00,317 --> 00:09:04,964
So now we can try the first one.

98
00:09:07,447 --> 00:09:08,788
I'll just keep a timer going.

99
00:09:09,490 --> 00:09:30,256
So this body is subject to disease.

100
00:10:11,428 --> 00:10:14,267
This body is of a nature to fall ill.

101
00:11:04,972 --> 00:11:14,089
This body has not gone beyond sickness.

102
00:12:10,751 --> 00:12:13,287
This body is subject to aging.

103
00:13:11,485 --> 00:13:14,727
This body has not gone beyond aging.

104
00:14:08,876 --> 00:14:12,475
This body is now in a process of aging.

105
00:15:08,529 --> 00:15:11,301
This body is subject to death.

106
00:16:08,284 --> 00:16:10,971
This body has not gone beyond death.

107
00:17:07,786 --> 00:17:10,117
This body will die.

108
00:18:11,287 --> 00:18:20,435
I will be parted and separated from everyone and everything that is dear and pleasing to me.

109
00:19:10,957 --> 00:19:15,481
I am the owner of my actions of mind, speech and body.

110
00:20:10,609 --> 00:20:13,481
I will inherit the results of my actions.

111
00:21:07,866 --> 00:21:11,771
Don't forget there's a dark and a bright side to these statements.

112
00:21:12,732 --> 00:21:17,097
And you can bring both wholesome and unwholesome actions to mind.

113
00:21:18,219 --> 00:21:21,221
And in that way, you can sort of balance the act, you might say.

114
00:21:21,423 --> 00:21:25,267
And I dare say that in the end, you're on the positive side.

115
00:21:28,411 --> 00:21:33,856
I am born each moment, each day, each lifetime of my actions.

116
00:22:28,781 --> 00:22:50,959
I form relations through my actions.

117
00:23:08,692 --> 00:23:32,067
I live dependent on my actions.

118
00:24:27,970 --> 00:24:33,423
Whatever I do, for good or for ill, I shall inherit the results.

119
00:25:30,204 --> 00:25:34,932
to balance these reflections.

120
00:25:35,634 --> 00:25:50,277
We can either really consider the wonderful things we've done in our lives, and there will be them, they will be there if you care to look, or we can do this reflection on gratitude and the joys of life.

121
00:25:50,297 --> 00:25:52,820
So to make sure that it's actually worth living.

122
00:25:53,981 --> 00:25:57,628
So I'll scroll this down in case you want to see it.

123
00:25:58,570 --> 00:26:04,662
So it's just a few subjects there.

124
00:26:07,047 --> 00:26:12,497
So just bringing to mind our mother, father, family, friends.

125
00:26:42,615 --> 00:26:48,968
All our upbringing and education, all the people, all the teachers that have helped us.

126
00:26:53,537 --> 00:26:59,807
And if we had a religious upbringing.

127
00:26:59,827 --> 00:27:01,771
And the teachers that have helped us spiritually.

128
00:27:13,311 --> 00:27:15,434
Then there's all the medical practitioners.

129
00:27:33,980 --> 00:27:40,230
And there's the gifts of our society, our culture, of the world, of nature.

130
00:28:00,393 --> 00:28:04,118
And then there's the miracle of waking up in the morning.

131
00:28:04,138 --> 00:28:04,920
Consciousness.

132
00:28:06,001 --> 00:28:07,683
The preciousness of human life.

133
00:28:18,560 --> 00:28:19,803
Remember we were given it.

134
00:28:22,788 --> 00:28:24,210
We weren't in control of that.

135
00:28:24,230 --> 00:28:27,935
There's very little we're actually in control of.

136
00:28:38,412 --> 00:28:41,605
And then finally, just the preciousness of the Dhamma.

137
00:29:03,521 --> 00:29:25,296
So at this point, you can either continue this contemplation, and what you can do is go back to the one or two that seemed to really touch you, that had an effect on you, and to sort of work with it gently, just accepting its truth value.

138
00:29:27,699 --> 00:29:28,820
And then...

139
00:29:30,234 --> 00:29:33,721
Or then you can just return to Vipassana.

140
00:29:34,903 --> 00:29:37,188
Okay, so that's what we'll do now.

141
00:29:37,509 --> 00:29:39,211
I'll end this.

142
00:29:44,643 --> 00:29:49,070
I'll try and make this a bit smaller so you can see it.

143
00:30:00,593 --> 00:30:01,153
Okay.

144
00:30:03,635 --> 00:30:05,137
That's about as best as I can get it.

145
00:30:12,224 --> 00:30:16,269
So, feel free to continue in any way you wish.

146
00:30:18,071 --> 00:30:19,973
And then we'll take the refs as a precepts.

147
00:30:23,257 --> 00:30:24,939
There's not much time left, actually.

148
00:30:26,460 --> 00:30:28,001
I've spent a bit of time on this.

149
00:30:41,161 --> 00:30:45,317
I'll be putting this document up onto the website, by the way.

150
00:30:46,804 --> 00:30:48,791
I think it might already be there.

151
00:31:19,130 --> 00:31:19,315
Thank you.

152
00:36:36,784 --> 00:36:38,266
So just a final word.

153
00:36:40,030 --> 00:36:53,347
As we practice this, what we're doing is we're moving from an intellectual understanding of these statements into a heart acceptance.

154
00:36:53,849 --> 00:36:56,632
So a sense of them being digested.

155
00:36:57,773 --> 00:37:03,922
And when we accept the truth value of these things, the gift, of course,

156
00:37:04,088 --> 00:37:09,614
is a feeling of safety, a feeling of equanimity.

157
00:37:10,994 --> 00:37:16,681
And that allows us to feel inwardly more serene, just this acceptance of the way things are.

158
00:37:17,521 --> 00:37:22,146
And the fact that we have very little control over sickness, aging, and death.

159
00:37:23,588 --> 00:37:30,355
And it's just allowing that thought to be accepted within the heart.

160
00:37:30,556 --> 00:37:31,817
That's the thing, you see.

161
00:37:32,202 --> 00:37:38,010
And if you do this exercise, you don't have to do it for so long in the morning.

162
00:37:38,389 --> 00:37:42,135
You know, the first almost one of the first thing you do before you even sit.

163
00:37:44,177 --> 00:37:50,686
Then after a while, just just just reading them through is enough.

164
00:37:50,706 --> 00:37:56,994
It's enough to put you into that right mindset of not being surprised if something goes wrong during the day.

165
00:37:57,920 --> 00:37:58,681
Okay.

166
00:37:59,501 --> 00:38:01,364
So I hope you found this useful.

167
00:38:01,824 --> 00:38:13,800
And according to the Buddha, remember, just the contemplation of death, never mind all the vipassana and all the other stuff, just contemplating death is a path to nibbana.

168
00:38:14,201 --> 00:38:19,148
That's how incisive, how wonderful it can be just to do that.

169
00:38:19,869 --> 00:38:24,695
And the paradox is, of course, that everything becomes precious.

170
00:38:25,054 --> 00:38:27,858
Life becomes absolutely more wonderful because of it.

171
00:38:28,177 --> 00:38:43,614
There's a book by a man called Becker called The Denial of Death, and he goes into what happens when we deny it, when we're in a state of aversion to it.

172
00:38:43,635 --> 00:38:55,347
And it's really interesting how money is somehow connected to the aversion to death, you know, getting as much as we can to preserve ourselves.

173
00:38:56,003 --> 00:39:14,735
And the other one, which, of course, we do know from COVID is, you know, our going to our toiletry is part of death because, of course, all our shit, if you'll excuse the word, is dead.

174
00:39:15,157 --> 00:39:15,376
Right.

175
00:39:15,637 --> 00:39:20,847
And that's why during COVID, everybody went out and bought loads of toilet paper.

176
00:39:22,344 --> 00:39:27,532
So that's sort of what happens if we don't contemplate death.

177
00:39:27,554 --> 00:39:30,557
We spend a lot of money on toilet paper.

178
00:39:30,577 --> 00:39:39,492
So I hope my words or this little practice has been of some assistance and that it will help you in your journey towards full liberation from all suffering.

